{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492409"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1052"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1052"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.36,0.26,0.04,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104137"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1052"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86460"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1894"},{"type":"tags","id":"2123"},{"type":"tags","id":"3477"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44628"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104137"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with recurrent urinary tract infections. He reports seven proven infections in the previous 12 months. He gets up twice at night to pass urine and has a relatively poor stream, with some terminal dribbling. His medical history is significant only for a hernia repair, and he does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His bladder does not appear to be distended. Digital rectal examination reveals a large, soft, non-tender prostate. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUltrasound: normal kidneys, prostate volume 30 mL, normal bladder with pre-void volume 500 mL and post-void residual 300 mL\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERecent urine culture: \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E, successfully treated with antibiotics\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPSA: 5.1 \u00b5g/L (reference range: \u0026lt;6.51 \u00b5g/L)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Long-term prophylactic trimethoprim","Commence dutasteride","Transurethral resection of the prostate","Prostate biopsy","Urodynamic studies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with chronic urinary retention secondary to benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), complicated by recurrent urinary tract infections. His prostate volume of 30 ml is over the average adult size of 20 -25 ml. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Etransurethral resection of the prostate (TURP)\u003C/strong\u003E. This procedure is considered the gold standard surgical treatment for BPH with chronic urinary retention. TURP would address the underlying cause of the patient\u0027s recurrent infections by relieving the bladder outlet obstruction and reducing post-void residual volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-term prophylactic trimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate long-term solution for this patient. While antibiotics may temporarily suppress infections, they do not address the underlying cause of chronic retention. Moreover, long-term antibiotic use can lead to antibiotic resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing dutasteride\u003C/strong\u003E is also not the best approach. While dutasteride can help reduce prostate size over time, it would not provide immediate relief of the chronic retention. Given the patient\u0027s age and severity of symptoms, a more definitive treatment is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstate biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. The patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are consistent with BPH, and there are no specific concerns for prostate cancer that would necessitate a biopsy at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrodynamic studies\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially useful in some cases of lower urinary tract symptoms, are not necessary before proceeding to TURP in this patient with clear evidence of chronic retention and recurrent infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of chronic urinary retention is supported by the post-void residual volume of 300 mL, which is above the generally accepted threshold of 100-200 mL. The patient\u0027s history of recurrent urinary tract infections, nocturia, poor urinary stream, and terminal dribbling are all consistent with bladder outlet obstruction due to BPH. By addressing the underlying cause with TURP, the likelihood of recurrent urinary tract infections should significantly decrease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recurrent urinary tract infections secondary to chronic urinary retention are best treated by prostatectomy.","Chronic urinary retention is diagnosed by post-void residual volume greater than 100-200 mL.","Transurethral resection of the prostate (TURP) is the gold standard surgical treatment for benign prostatic hyperplasia with chronic urinary retention."],"references":["Nicolle LE. Urinary Tract Infections in the Older Adult. Clin Geriatr Med 2016; 32:523-38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27394021/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86460"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1052"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86460"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T14:53:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T14:53:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1052"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104137"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understan